1
00:00:27,269 --> 00:00:29,534
Kaaaate?

2
00:00:29,569 --> 00:00:30,901
You ready?

3
00:00:32,102 --> 00:00:34,868
Should I say, "This
chapter is so boring,

4
00:00:34,903 --> 00:00:38,834
my begonia committed suicide
when I read it out loud,"

5
00:00:38,869 --> 00:00:42,033
or, "Let's talk"?

6
00:00:42,068 --> 00:00:43,667
I like the first one.

7
00:00:43,702 --> 00:00:45,901
Yeah, me too.

8
00:00:45,936 --> 00:00:47,534
Oh, God, we're never
gonna make it.

9
00:00:47,569 --> 00:00:49,367
So we're just gonna get
the 6 to Grand Central?

10
00:00:49,402 --> 00:00:51,234
Well, I thought that
we would take the N here

11
00:00:51,269 --> 00:00:52,234
and then transfer.

12
00:00:52,269 --> 00:00:53,901
Heh.
Right.

13
00:00:56,434 --> 00:00:58,100
Ta-da!

14
00:00:58,135 --> 00:00:59,968
Wow!
Yeah.

15
00:01:00,003 --> 00:01:01,701
I mean, I know it's
little and it's dark

16
00:01:01,736 --> 00:01:03,767
and the hallways
smell like cabbage...

17
00:01:03,802 --> 00:01:05,334
And it's in Brooklyn.

18
00:01:05,369 --> 00:01:06,767
But it's mine!

19
00:01:06,802 --> 00:01:08,567
There's--
there's no roommate,

20
00:01:08,602 --> 00:01:11,200
there's no cigarette butts
in the coffee cups,

21
00:01:11,235 --> 00:01:13,701
no-- no toenails
in the sink.

22
00:01:13,736 --> 00:01:15,334
Ew!

23
00:01:15,369 --> 00:01:17,300
You're glowing.

24
00:01:17,335 --> 00:01:19,200
I'm happy.

25
00:01:19,235 --> 00:01:21,701
No, I mean it.
You got this weird glow.

26
00:01:24,133 --> 00:01:25,701
So, whaddaya think?

27
00:01:25,736 --> 00:01:27,634
Oh! And, uh, they
fixed up the kitchen.

28
00:01:27,669 --> 00:01:29,567
What are you gonna do
with a kitchen?

29
00:01:29,602 --> 00:01:32,033
I'm cooking.
Mm-hmm.

30
00:01:32,068 --> 00:01:34,467
Friday, as a matter
of fact, for Matt.

31
00:01:34,502 --> 00:01:36,467
It's a special meal.

32
00:01:36,502 --> 00:01:37,968
What's special?

33
00:01:38,003 --> 00:01:40,234
Oh, it's mine,
it's mine!

34
00:01:40,269 --> 00:01:43,100
It's all mine!
Thanks for coming!

35
00:01:48,669 --> 00:01:51,834
Matt? Whaddaya think?

36
00:01:51,869 --> 00:01:53,367
Forget the packing boxes

37
00:01:53,402 --> 00:01:55,434
and I'm gonna get
some more furniture.

38
00:01:55,469 --> 00:01:58,133
Well, I have a bed.

39
00:01:58,168 --> 00:02:01,067
And just because I never cook
doesn't mean I can't.

40
00:02:01,102 --> 00:02:04,234
It just means it's a pain
to cook for one person.

41
00:02:04,269 --> 00:02:06,300
Mmm. Mmm.

42
00:02:07,501 --> 00:02:09,934
Matt?

43
00:02:09,969 --> 00:02:13,934
Well, I hope you like
what I'm making.

44
00:02:13,969 --> 00:02:17,868
It's a special meal because
it's a very special night.

45
00:02:17,903 --> 00:02:22,767
I said, it's a special meal
because it's a special night.

46
00:02:26,834 --> 00:02:29,100
I have a present for you.

47
00:02:36,501 --> 00:02:38,934
I can't do it.

48
00:03:11,634 --> 00:03:13,400
Of course
the watering schedules

49
00:03:13,435 --> 00:03:15,367
could be inserted
into the paragraph.

50
00:03:15,402 --> 00:03:19,300
I'm not suggesting it's
a physical impossibility.

51
00:03:19,335 --> 00:03:20,901
Esthetically,
it's a train wreck,

52
00:03:20,936 --> 00:03:22,434
but it can be done.

53
00:03:22,469 --> 00:03:24,234
You could also decide
to use italics

54
00:03:24,269 --> 00:03:25,968
if you want to complete
the destruction.

55
00:03:30,601 --> 00:03:31,934
What's wrong?

56
00:03:34,202 --> 00:03:35,434
It's something
I said, isn't it?

57
00:03:35,469 --> 00:03:37,901
My wicked tongue.

58
00:03:37,936 --> 00:03:39,234
No.

59
00:03:39,269 --> 00:03:40,534
Alright, mea culpa.

60
00:03:40,569 --> 00:03:43,033
I wanted a different editor;
I admit it.

61
00:03:43,068 --> 00:03:44,968
But let me come right out
and say you've done

62
00:03:45,003 --> 00:03:48,200
an excellent job...
for a young woman.

63
00:03:49,868 --> 00:03:51,467
Thanks.

64
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:20,868
"Dear Kate,
I honestly did think

65
00:04:20,903 --> 00:04:23,467
"it could work between us

66
00:04:23,502 --> 00:04:27,367
"and it is completely
my fault that it couldn't.

67
00:04:27,402 --> 00:04:30,767
"You did nothing wrong
except ask me to lunch.

68
00:04:33,033 --> 00:04:34,934
"If you've got
the heart to read this,

69
00:04:34,969 --> 00:04:38,968
"it will explain everything
better than I could.

70
00:04:39,003 --> 00:04:40,868
"Be warned, though.

71
00:04:40,903 --> 00:04:44,534
"There are parts that will be
hard to get through.

72
00:04:44,569 --> 00:04:48,067
"'Sorry' is too weak a word.

73
00:04:48,102 --> 00:04:49,634
Matt."

74
00:05:07,367 --> 00:05:09,000
Who?

75
00:05:14,467 --> 00:05:17,300
Eighteen months ago.

76
00:05:19,334 --> 00:05:21,400
"Dear Nicholas...

77
00:05:21,435 --> 00:05:25,567
"as I write the first
entry in this diary,

78
00:05:25,602 --> 00:05:30,734
you were not yet born,
but I know you will be..."

79
00:05:30,769 --> 00:05:33,734
So, I've decided
to keep a record

80
00:05:33,769 --> 00:05:36,100
of your childhood
for you to look back on

81
00:05:36,135 --> 00:05:37,501
when you grow up.

82
00:05:37,536 --> 00:05:40,200
It's important to know
where you came from, Nicky.

83
00:05:40,235 --> 00:05:42,934
Gives you roots.

84
00:05:42,969 --> 00:05:46,267
So I'm gonna begin
before the beginning,

85
00:05:46,302 --> 00:05:48,467
before I even met
your father.

86
00:05:48,502 --> 00:05:50,200
I was still a doctor
in Boston.

87
00:05:50,235 --> 00:05:53,300
Dr. Brunik,
report to the neuro ICU.

88
00:05:53,335 --> 00:05:55,300
Suzanne.

89
00:05:55,335 --> 00:05:57,033
Michael.

90
00:05:58,200 --> 00:05:59,434
See you
at the house, okay?

91
00:05:59,469 --> 00:06:00,634
You got it.

92
00:06:26,335 --> 00:06:28,167
Ugh.

93
00:06:35,367 --> 00:06:37,534
Are you alright, miss?
I'm a doctor.

94
00:06:37,569 --> 00:06:39,634
I think I'm...

95
00:06:39,669 --> 00:06:41,100
gonna have
a heart attack.

96
00:06:41,135 --> 00:06:42,067
Oh, my God!

97
00:06:58,235 --> 00:07:00,200
I'm only 33.

98
00:07:00,235 --> 00:07:01,467
Calm, Suzanne.

99
00:07:01,502 --> 00:07:02,701
Yes, calm.

100
00:07:02,736 --> 00:07:04,868
You had a double bypass,
not botox.

101
00:07:04,903 --> 00:07:07,601
But I'm only 33, Phil.

102
00:07:07,636 --> 00:07:10,434
With a family history
of heart disease.

103
00:07:10,469 --> 00:07:14,200
Which doesn't seem
to be here in your record.

104
00:07:14,235 --> 00:07:15,734
Hmm.

105
00:07:15,769 --> 00:07:17,434
I forgot.

106
00:07:17,469 --> 00:07:18,667
Uh-huh.

107
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,300
Well, I can tell you
that at auction

108
00:07:24,335 --> 00:07:26,334
a piece of depression glass
in this condition--

109
00:07:26,369 --> 00:07:28,534
You're late again.

110
00:07:30,569 --> 00:07:32,167
Michael, I am so bored.

111
00:07:32,202 --> 00:07:33,767
Will you please take me
out to dinner?

112
00:07:33,802 --> 00:07:35,200
Please, please, please?

113
00:07:35,235 --> 00:07:38,033
I want something fat
and I want something greasy

114
00:07:38,068 --> 00:07:40,834
and I want...

115
00:07:43,567 --> 00:07:45,467
Uh-oh.

116
00:07:45,502 --> 00:07:47,801
Suzanne, how long have
we been seeing each other?

117
00:07:47,836 --> 00:07:49,968
Six months?

118
00:07:50,003 --> 00:07:52,234
And did you consider our
relationship a serious one?

119
00:07:52,269 --> 00:07:54,234
Don't use the professor voice,
Michael, please.

120
00:07:54,269 --> 00:07:55,234
It drives me insane.

121
00:07:55,269 --> 00:07:56,634
Fine, regular voice.

122
00:07:56,669 --> 00:07:59,234
Why the hell
didn't you tell me
you had a heart problem?

123
00:07:59,269 --> 00:08:00,534
God, I can't--

124
00:08:00,569 --> 00:08:01,901
Just one last time.

125
00:08:04,367 --> 00:08:05,467
There was no problem.

126
00:08:05,502 --> 00:08:07,601
There was a history.

127
00:08:07,636 --> 00:08:10,434
Well, there was history
of measles too, Michael.

128
00:08:10,469 --> 00:08:13,067
And you put that
in your medical record.

129
00:08:13,102 --> 00:08:15,934
I took a look at your workup,
Suzanne; it isn't good.

130
00:08:15,969 --> 00:08:18,801
There's damage
to your heart.

131
00:08:18,836 --> 00:08:20,534
It isn't life-threatening,
but it is limiting.

132
00:08:20,569 --> 00:08:23,601
And one of the limitations--
now I consulted
with cardio on this,

133
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:24,901
so don't shoot
the messenger--

134
00:08:24,936 --> 00:08:27,133
Just...
Okay.

135
00:08:27,168 --> 00:08:29,100
I'm afraid we've come
to the conclusion

136
00:08:29,135 --> 00:08:32,334
that a pregnancy would pose
a real risk to your health.

137
00:08:35,434 --> 00:08:38,868
You know I want
children, Suzanne.

138
00:08:38,903 --> 00:08:40,367
You know it's one
of the most important--

139
00:08:40,402 --> 00:08:42,067
I know.

140
00:08:42,102 --> 00:08:43,934
If you'd just told me.

141
00:08:45,467 --> 00:08:47,634
Wait a minute.

142
00:08:47,669 --> 00:08:49,167
Wait, let me--
let me get this straight.

143
00:08:49,202 --> 00:08:52,934
Are you saying that
because my family

144
00:08:52,969 --> 00:08:55,334
has a history of heart disease,
that I don't have

145
00:08:55,369 --> 00:08:57,601
the right to--
to fall in love?

146
00:08:57,636 --> 00:09:00,167
Or-- or to have a relationship
or to get married?

147
00:09:00,202 --> 00:09:01,601
I mean,
is this what you're--

148
00:09:01,636 --> 00:09:03,701
is this what
you're saying, Michael?

149
00:09:03,736 --> 00:09:05,801
Huh?

150
00:09:11,100 --> 00:09:12,234
I'm sorry.

151
00:09:24,302 --> 00:09:25,200
Bastard.

152
00:09:26,834 --> 00:09:28,300
Did you read
the last page?

153
00:09:28,335 --> 00:09:29,367
What?

154
00:09:29,402 --> 00:09:30,567
No.

155
00:09:30,602 --> 00:09:32,300
But you're
going to, right?

156
00:09:32,335 --> 00:09:33,701
Why should I?

157
00:09:33,736 --> 00:09:36,367
Maybe Michael dies
at the end or something.
I don't know.

158
00:09:36,402 --> 00:09:39,434
Well, I know.

159
00:09:39,469 --> 00:09:41,467
See, Matt's
the rebound guy.

160
00:09:41,502 --> 00:09:44,934
Suzanne found him
and they're together right now

161
00:09:44,969 --> 00:09:47,534
living happily ever after.

162
00:09:47,569 --> 00:09:50,767
And that's all
I need to know.

163
00:09:53,567 --> 00:09:56,334
What did you have?

164
00:09:56,369 --> 00:09:57,901
Half of yours.

165
00:10:24,534 --> 00:10:28,167
Weak. Weak.

166
00:10:31,634 --> 00:10:33,667
He walked out with his art

167
00:10:33,702 --> 00:10:37,300
and his antiques...
and my whole life.

168
00:10:37,335 --> 00:10:38,868
I had nothing left.

169
00:10:38,903 --> 00:10:42,467
No lover, no child,
no plans.

170
00:10:42,502 --> 00:10:44,801
I needed a change, Nicky.

171
00:10:44,836 --> 00:10:49,701
Not just a small change;
a sea change.

172
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:53,133
Until I began college,
I had spent every summer

173
00:10:53,168 --> 00:10:54,734
on Martha's Vineyard.

174
00:10:54,769 --> 00:10:56,234
And I remembered
it was the last

175
00:10:56,269 --> 00:10:58,033
best place in the world.

176
00:11:08,868 --> 00:11:12,167
So, with all of my savings,
I bought the practice

177
00:11:12,202 --> 00:11:16,334
of a retiring GP
who was headed back to Boston.

178
00:11:19,734 --> 00:11:22,033
We were switching lives.

179
00:11:27,100 --> 00:11:30,868
I told him I felt that
I'd gotten the better deal.

180
00:11:54,367 --> 00:11:58,334
And when I stood there
in that house that was mine,

181
00:11:58,369 --> 00:12:01,968
everything snapped
into place.

182
00:12:02,003 --> 00:12:04,934
I knew that I had made
the right decision.

183
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,801
By some extraordinary
twist of luck,

184
00:12:13,836 --> 00:12:16,601
I had found
my perfect place.

185
00:12:24,234 --> 00:12:25,300
You the doc?

186
00:12:25,335 --> 00:12:27,601
Uh, yeah.
Something wrong?

187
00:12:27,636 --> 00:12:30,200
No, I'm from
across the road.
Oh.

188
00:12:30,235 --> 00:12:33,501
Yeah. I said to Carl,
my husband Carl,

189
00:12:33,536 --> 00:12:35,200
I said, somebody
went and did it.

190
00:12:35,235 --> 00:12:36,467
Couldn't be a local.

191
00:12:36,502 --> 00:12:38,434
No, no, I'm from Boston--

192
00:12:38,469 --> 00:12:40,100
Then he said it's a doc
from the city.

193
00:12:40,135 --> 00:12:41,434
And I said, well,
that's a blessing,

194
00:12:41,469 --> 00:12:42,801
'cause when we lost
old Doc MacLaren,

195
00:12:42,836 --> 00:12:44,901
I thought we were just
outta luck down here.

196
00:12:44,936 --> 00:12:46,467
And me with two
little ones.

197
00:12:46,502 --> 00:12:47,567
You know, I have
a family practice--

198
00:12:47,602 --> 00:12:48,901
And then Carl says,
does he know

199
00:12:48,936 --> 00:12:50,534
what she's getting
herself into?

200
00:12:50,569 --> 00:12:52,534
And I said, well,
I don't expect old Doc

201
00:12:52,569 --> 00:12:54,033
give her the grand tour.

202
00:12:54,068 --> 00:12:55,200
He could barely walk,
ya know?

203
00:12:55,235 --> 00:12:56,901
He had this thing
with his hip?

204
00:12:56,936 --> 00:12:57,934
You got a minute?

205
00:12:57,969 --> 00:12:59,133
Um...

206
00:13:02,434 --> 00:13:04,968
Take a whiff.

207
00:13:05,003 --> 00:13:07,000
Think it's low tide,
don't ya?

208
00:13:07,035 --> 00:13:08,467
Septic tank.

209
00:13:08,502 --> 00:13:09,934
Oh, well,
that's not good.

210
00:13:13,801 --> 00:13:17,033
Don't worry; there's six
more layers under that.

211
00:13:20,133 --> 00:13:21,734
Watch.

212
00:13:26,836 --> 00:13:29,000
But hey,
I'm the glass-half-empty girl,

213
00:13:29,035 --> 00:13:30,400
ya know?

214
00:13:30,435 --> 00:13:31,534
It's a beautiful place.

215
00:13:31,569 --> 00:13:33,901
Well, it could be.

216
00:13:33,936 --> 00:13:35,367
Anyway, we're happy
to have you here.

217
00:13:35,402 --> 00:13:37,300
Welcome to the Vineyard.
I'm Melanie Boom.

218
00:13:37,335 --> 00:13:39,601
Oh, Suzanne--
Bedford, yeah.

219
00:13:39,636 --> 00:13:40,801
And don't worry
about a thing.

220
00:13:40,836 --> 00:13:42,701
I know this great
handyman-painter type.

221
00:13:42,736 --> 00:13:44,100
Better than Picasso.

222
00:13:44,135 --> 00:13:45,534
I'll get him out here,
no problem.

223
00:15:08,767 --> 00:15:10,868
Hello?

224
00:15:12,267 --> 00:15:14,501
Hello?

225
00:15:16,601 --> 00:15:17,968
Hell--

226
00:15:19,067 --> 00:15:20,767
Uh...

227
00:15:20,802 --> 00:15:22,434
Picasso?

228
00:15:22,469 --> 00:15:23,834
You've been talkin'
to Melanie.

229
00:15:23,869 --> 00:15:25,534
Yeah.

230
00:15:25,569 --> 00:15:26,701
You-- you started already?

231
00:15:26,736 --> 00:15:29,701
Yeah. You owe me
140 bucks so far.

232
00:15:29,736 --> 00:15:32,133
I'm just kiddin'.

233
00:15:32,168 --> 00:15:34,901
I'm checkin',
makin' some notes.

234
00:15:34,936 --> 00:15:36,667
I'll be right down.

235
00:15:44,901 --> 00:15:46,367
Did Melanie, uh,
show you around?

236
00:15:46,402 --> 00:15:48,601
Yes, she-- she gave me
the grand tour.

237
00:15:48,636 --> 00:15:49,767
She tell you
about the roof?

238
00:15:49,802 --> 00:15:52,501
No.
Uh, the shingles?

239
00:15:52,536 --> 00:15:54,501
No.
The, um...

240
00:15:56,334 --> 00:15:57,901
Don't worry.

241
00:15:57,936 --> 00:16:00,367
Yeah, that's--
that's what Melanie said.

242
00:16:00,402 --> 00:16:02,300
I'll have it done
by the millennium.

243
00:16:02,335 --> 00:16:03,934
But the millennium
was two years ago.

244
00:16:03,969 --> 00:16:05,300
The next millennium.

245
00:16:05,335 --> 00:16:06,601
Oh.

246
00:16:06,636 --> 00:16:08,300
Do you know your way
around the island?

247
00:16:09,901 --> 00:16:11,634
I could, uh,
show you around sometime.

248
00:16:11,669 --> 00:16:15,400
Oh, um...

249
00:16:15,435 --> 00:16:16,734
No, I, uh...

250
00:16:16,769 --> 00:16:19,400
Or I could just
fix your house and shut up.

251
00:16:19,435 --> 00:16:20,601
No, it's-- it's--

252
00:16:20,636 --> 00:16:23,133
It's not that I don't--
It--

253
00:16:26,100 --> 00:16:27,300
It's just a bad time.

254
00:16:27,335 --> 00:16:29,634
No problem.

255
00:16:43,968 --> 00:16:46,834
Ah...

256
00:16:54,100 --> 00:16:56,033
The doctor in, Miss?

257
00:16:56,068 --> 00:16:58,667
Uh, yeah,
I'm the doctor.

258
00:17:00,234 --> 00:17:02,734
Ah...
Uh...

259
00:17:02,769 --> 00:17:04,467
Do I need
an appointment?

260
00:17:05,669 --> 00:17:10,100
I, uh, think
I can squeeze you in.

261
00:17:10,135 --> 00:17:12,400
Why don't you
have a seat?

262
00:17:13,801 --> 00:17:15,534
So what seems
to be the problem?

263
00:17:15,569 --> 00:17:17,734
What ain't?
Okay.

