00:17:21,335 --> 00:17:23,033
You did? When?

266
00:17:23,068 --> 00:17:24,367
Last week.

267
00:17:24,402 --> 00:17:26,567
You had a heart attack
last week?

268
00:17:26,602 --> 00:17:28,767
It sure felt like one.

269
00:17:28,802 --> 00:17:30,601
Well, did you see
a doctor?

270
00:17:30,636 --> 00:17:32,300
Seein' one now.

271
00:17:32,335 --> 00:17:34,901
Ah, okay.

272
00:17:34,936 --> 00:17:37,234
Do you have any
other complaints, Mr., uh...

273
00:17:37,269 --> 00:17:38,400
Earl'll do.

274
00:17:38,435 --> 00:17:39,801
Earl.

275
00:17:39,836 --> 00:17:42,567
Well, since you're askin',
I got the gout.

276
00:17:42,602 --> 00:17:45,234
Pretty sore.
Swelled up foot.

277
00:17:45,269 --> 00:17:46,968
How'd you get your shoe on?

278
00:17:47,003 --> 00:17:48,234
Oh, it wasn't easy.

279
00:17:49,567 --> 00:17:51,534
Alright, is there
anything else?

280
00:17:51,569 --> 00:17:54,100
I got a list.

281
00:17:56,400 --> 00:17:58,200
Uh...

282
00:18:05,234 --> 00:18:07,501
Excuse me.
Sorry.

283
00:18:25,067 --> 00:18:26,067
Hi.

284
00:18:36,367 --> 00:18:38,701
Come on over.

285
00:18:48,968 --> 00:18:51,734
I write.

286
00:18:51,769 --> 00:18:54,567
Pardon?

287
00:18:54,602 --> 00:18:57,501
Oh, you got that look.

288
00:18:57,536 --> 00:18:59,100
What look?

289
00:18:59,135 --> 00:19:01,601
Why is he
a house painter?

290
00:19:01,636 --> 00:19:03,801
No, I don't.
Yes, you do.

291
00:19:03,836 --> 00:19:06,868
Well, I'll tell ya
if you wanna know.

292
00:19:06,903 --> 00:19:07,868
Okay.

293
00:19:07,903 --> 00:19:09,634
I'm an open book.

294
00:19:09,669 --> 00:19:10,834
Okay.

295
00:19:10,869 --> 00:19:12,934
Okay, if you're gonna
beat it outta me...

296
00:19:15,369 --> 00:19:17,868
I went to work
at my old man's company

297
00:19:17,903 --> 00:19:20,167
after I graduated
from Brown.

298
00:19:20,202 --> 00:19:23,300
My father was proud of me,
which was important, I guess.

299
00:19:23,335 --> 00:19:25,167
So I worked there
through most of my 20's,

300
00:19:25,202 --> 00:19:28,667
and then my father
passed away,

301
00:19:28,702 --> 00:19:31,467
and I realized
that I had nobody left

302
00:19:31,502 --> 00:19:36,133
to prove myself to,
and that... I hated it.

303
00:19:36,168 --> 00:19:39,501
And I drank too much
and I did too many drugs

304
00:19:39,536 --> 00:19:42,567
and hated the city and...

305
00:19:42,602 --> 00:19:44,400
I knew I had to make
a sea change.

306
00:19:48,601 --> 00:19:50,901
Thank you.

307
00:19:50,936 --> 00:19:54,100
See, the thing is,
at Brown I wrote.

308
00:19:54,135 --> 00:19:57,133
And I had this one
great professor

309
00:19:57,168 --> 00:19:59,567
who told me that
I'd be a writer.

310
00:19:59,602 --> 00:20:03,033
He had, uh--
he had faith in me.

311
00:20:03,068 --> 00:20:06,167
So I went back to him
and I asked,

312
00:20:06,202 --> 00:20:07,701
"Is this stupid?"

313
00:20:07,736 --> 00:20:12,434
And he said,
"It's never stupid
to do what you want."

314
00:20:12,469 --> 00:20:13,901
Which I realize now
is a crock.

315
00:20:13,936 --> 00:20:16,300
But at the time,
it's what I wanted to hear.

316
00:20:16,335 --> 00:20:18,434
So, um, I moved back
to the only place

317
00:20:18,469 --> 00:20:20,234
that I ever loved
and I began.

318
00:20:20,269 --> 00:20:24,234
That was about
eight years ago and...

319
00:20:24,269 --> 00:20:28,868
so far, I've sold...

320
00:20:28,903 --> 00:20:31,367
almost one story.

321
00:20:32,536 --> 00:20:35,234
The handyman thing
is how I support myself.

322
00:20:35,269 --> 00:20:39,067
I write.
I write every single day.

323
00:20:39,102 --> 00:20:41,334
Doesn't matter
if anyone reads it

324
00:20:41,369 --> 00:20:44,033
or doesn't read it.

325
00:20:44,068 --> 00:20:46,033
I write.

326
00:20:46,068 --> 00:20:48,534
Only thing
I'm serious about.

327
00:20:53,968 --> 00:20:56,467
I didn't know doctors
ate this kind of food.

328
00:20:56,502 --> 00:20:59,901
A Sam's clamburger?

329
00:20:59,936 --> 00:21:03,934
Ah, well, bad days,
small comfort.

330
00:21:03,969 --> 00:21:06,434
Here you go, Matt.
Thank you.

331
00:21:06,469 --> 00:21:07,901
Oh, no, no, no.
You don't have to--

332
00:21:07,936 --> 00:21:12,000
No, I'm runnin' the bill up
on this new lady in town.

333
00:21:15,501 --> 00:21:17,968
So, if your last name
is Picasso,

334
00:21:18,003 --> 00:21:20,367
what's your first name?

335
00:21:20,402 --> 00:21:22,267
Matthew.

336
00:21:22,302 --> 00:21:26,467
Matthew "Picasso" Harrelson.

337
00:21:26,502 --> 00:21:28,434
Welcome to the Vineyard.

338
00:21:28,469 --> 00:21:29,901
Thank you.

339
00:21:29,936 --> 00:21:32,100
Oh, God.

340
00:21:32,135 --> 00:21:35,133
Oh, God, that's the--

341
00:21:35,168 --> 00:21:37,734
She made it up!
That's not Matt at all!

342
00:21:37,769 --> 00:21:40,000
That's not him.

343
00:21:45,968 --> 00:21:49,033
Mr. Harrelson, hi.
I'm Kate Wilkes.

344
00:21:49,068 --> 00:21:52,033
It's so good
to finally meet you.

345
00:21:52,068 --> 00:21:55,200
Well, please come in.
Sit down.

346
00:21:55,235 --> 00:21:57,968
Um, here.

347
00:21:58,003 --> 00:21:59,901
Can I first say that...

348
00:21:59,936 --> 00:22:02,501
I love your stories,
especially the ones

349
00:22:02,536 --> 00:22:04,501
that you've written
most recently.

350
00:22:04,536 --> 00:22:07,133
They show a dramatic
improvement.

351
00:22:07,168 --> 00:22:11,133
Um, they're tougher,
more honestly emotional.

352
00:22:11,168 --> 00:22:13,100
They made me cry.

353
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:18,667
Um...

354
00:22:21,567 --> 00:22:23,334
Well, as you know,
ten stories

355
00:22:23,369 --> 00:22:24,868
have been chosen
for your book.

356
00:22:24,903 --> 00:22:27,167
Might I suggest that
we meet once a week

357
00:22:27,202 --> 00:22:31,133
for the next ten weeks
and tackle one story at a time.

358
00:22:31,168 --> 00:22:33,067
How does that sound?

359
00:22:33,102 --> 00:22:34,501
That's fine.

360
00:22:34,536 --> 00:22:36,234
Fine. Good.

361
00:22:36,269 --> 00:22:38,634
So, uh, if this
is a good time,

362
00:22:38,669 --> 00:22:41,634
then, why, let's say,
uh, every Friday at noon.

363
00:22:45,200 --> 00:22:46,367
Yes.

364
00:22:51,601 --> 00:22:53,167
Okay.

365
00:22:53,202 --> 00:22:55,267
Why don't we get
to work, then?

366
00:23:01,567 --> 00:23:04,167
Alright, Doc.

367
00:23:04,202 --> 00:23:06,934
What was your secret?

368
00:23:06,969 --> 00:23:09,067
What did you do for him?

369
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:14,200
Hey.
Hey.

370
00:23:20,003 --> 00:23:23,467
Ugh.

371
00:23:23,502 --> 00:23:24,767
Long day?

372
00:23:24,802 --> 00:23:27,133
No, it was a good day.

373
00:23:27,168 --> 00:23:29,334
Finally have
some patients.

374
00:23:29,369 --> 00:23:31,067
And that's not
counting Earl.

375
00:23:32,435 --> 00:23:33,868
Like who?

376
00:23:33,903 --> 00:23:35,601
Oh, I can't tell you that.

377
00:23:35,636 --> 00:23:37,834
That's doctor-client
confidentiality.

378
00:23:37,869 --> 00:23:42,033
Well, I saw Doris Latham
get rolled in.

379
00:23:42,068 --> 00:23:44,334
She's dead.
Did you figure that out?

380
00:23:44,369 --> 00:23:46,701
Oh, no.
She's only 92.

381
00:23:46,736 --> 00:23:48,534
Who else?

382
00:23:48,569 --> 00:23:50,434
I can't.

383
00:23:52,868 --> 00:23:55,567
Oh, what could happen
if you told me?

384
00:23:55,602 --> 00:23:57,133
Oh, jeez!
Oh!

385
00:23:59,801 --> 00:24:01,334
Whoa.
Here.

386
00:24:05,467 --> 00:24:06,968
I got it.
That's good.

387
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:10,267
I got it.
Alright.

388
00:24:10,302 --> 00:24:11,834
Got it?
Yeah.

389
00:24:13,033 --> 00:24:15,167
Ho.

390
00:24:20,534 --> 00:24:22,634
I-- I was just gonna
fix some dinner.

391
00:24:22,669 --> 00:24:24,601
You wanna stay?

392
00:24:24,636 --> 00:24:27,300
I'd love to.

393
00:24:33,267 --> 00:24:36,300
Voila!

394
00:24:36,335 --> 00:24:37,634
This is it?

395
00:24:37,669 --> 00:24:40,067
Oh, come on,
don't insult
the Suzanne.

396
00:24:42,602 --> 00:24:44,467
Oh, dear.

397
00:24:44,502 --> 00:24:45,534
Okay.
Madam.

398
00:24:45,569 --> 00:24:47,467
Thank you.

399
00:24:49,868 --> 00:24:50,868
Thank you.

400
00:24:50,903 --> 00:24:53,200
You're welcome.

401
00:24:53,235 --> 00:24:55,133
Watch your head.

402
00:24:55,168 --> 00:24:56,133
Ready?

403
00:24:56,168 --> 00:24:57,567
Does it even run?

404
00:24:57,602 --> 00:24:59,734
On and off.

405
00:24:59,769 --> 00:25:01,701
Ha ha!

406
00:25:01,736 --> 00:25:02,834
Oh.

407
00:25:04,934 --> 00:25:06,434
Like to take the helm?

408
00:25:06,469 --> 00:25:08,267
Should I?

409
00:25:08,302 --> 00:25:10,133
Come on.
Okay.

410
00:25:11,534 --> 00:25:13,467
Just steering, right?

411
00:25:13,502 --> 00:25:16,167
I don't have to
do anything fancy?

412
00:25:16,202 --> 00:25:18,501
I just hold on
to this thing.

413
00:25:18,536 --> 00:25:20,434
Okay.
Yes.

414
00:25:20,469 --> 00:25:22,300
Ready?
Okay, yes.

415
00:25:22,335 --> 00:25:23,534
Okay.

416
00:25:51,767 --> 00:25:52,868
Hi.

417
00:25:52,903 --> 00:25:55,100
Hey.
Matt.

418
00:25:58,734 --> 00:26:01,367
Hey, hold on a minute.

419
00:26:04,400 --> 00:26:06,167
Hey, Doc.

420
00:26:16,868 --> 00:26:18,534
What?

421
00:26:18,569 --> 00:26:19,701
Dance?

422
00:26:19,736 --> 00:26:21,734
No...

423
00:26:21,769 --> 00:26:24,200
It's not really
a dancing place,

424
00:26:24,235 --> 00:26:26,868
I don't think.

425
00:26:45,969 --> 00:26:48,200
Okay, okay,
stop, stop, stop.

426
00:28:04,736 --> 00:28:07,033
What?

427
00:28:08,936 --> 00:28:11,501
What's wrong?

428
00:28:23,903 --> 00:28:25,868
Nothing.

429
00:28:57,367 --> 00:28:59,000
Hi.

430
00:28:59,035 --> 00:29:00,734
You look, uh--

431
00:29:15,534 --> 00:29:17,734
So, um,
you know what?

432
00:29:17,769 --> 00:29:19,868
I didn't have any
breakfast this morning.

433
00:29:19,903 --> 00:29:21,634
I'm starving.

434
00:29:21,669 --> 00:29:22,767
Sorry?

435
00:29:22,802 --> 00:29:24,968
No, I mean that
we could, uh--

436
00:29:25,003 --> 00:29:28,567
we could go out
to lunch now,
on the company.

437
00:29:28,602 --> 00:29:31,901
And, you know, it would,
uh, we-- we would work there.

438
00:29:31,936 --> 00:29:34,334
It'd be like a--

439
00:29:34,369 --> 00:29:37,467
a working lunch,
but, um--

440
00:29:37,502 --> 00:29:38,767
Mmm.

441
00:29:40,133 --> 00:29:41,667
Okay.

442
00:29:43,767 --> 00:29:46,133
Okay.

443
00:29:48,003 --> 00:29:51,467
Thank you.

444
00:29:51,502 --> 00:29:54,968
It's where we take
our most important clients.

445
00:29:55,003 --> 00:30:00,133
Yeah, it's a little fancy,
but, uh, good food.

446
00:30:00,168 --> 00:30:02,767
The, um-- They have
a fish special every day

447
00:30:02,802 --> 00:30:04,100
that's not on the menu.

448
00:30:04,135 --> 00:30:05,167
You like fish?

449
00:30:05,202 --> 00:30:07,067
No.

450
00:30:07,102 --> 00:30:08,968
No? I thought, um--

451
00:30:09,003 --> 00:30:12,434
Isn't fishing,
like, a big deal
on Martha's Vineyard?

452
00:30:12,469 --> 00:30:13,767
Yes, it is.

453
00:30:13,802 --> 00:30:16,067
Yeah!
With the whaling and--

454
00:30:16,102 --> 00:30:17,501
That's Nantucket.

455
00:30:17,536 --> 00:30:20,167
Right, 'cause that's
the main--

456
00:30:23,636 --> 00:30:25,968
You know, they make guacamole
right at the table.

457
00:30:26,003 --> 00:30:27,033
Really?

458
00:30:27,068 --> 00:30:29,167
Yeah. They, uh,
bring over the avocados

459
00:30:29,202 --> 00:30:33,000
and then they mush 'em up,
and, um, you know,

460
00:30:33,035 --> 00:30:36,167
they just put the rest
of the stuff in, and, um...

461
00:30:38,701 --> 00:30:40,767
Well--

462
00:30:40,802 --> 00:30:42,267
Then they light it.

463
00:30:42,302 --> 00:30:45,667
Yeah. It's their
specialty here.

464
00:30:47,133 --> 00:30:49,501
Flaming guacamole.

465
00:30:55,534 --> 00:30:58,434
Personally, I like
the fish better.

466
00:30:59,767 --> 00:31:01,868
Well, it's a small town
about 50 miles

467
00:31:01,903 --> 00:31:03,434
outside of Raleigh.

468
00:31:03,469 --> 00:31:04,567
Tobaccy country.

469
00:31:04,602 --> 00:31:07,234
It's got one main road,
one school.

470
00:31:07,269 --> 00:31:09,934
Did you smoke?
Hmm?

471
00:31:09,969 --> 00:31:11,334
Tobaccy country.

472
00:31:11,369 --> 00:31:12,534
Oh.

473
00:31:12,569 --> 00:31:16,667
Yeah, well...
everybody smoked.

474
00:31:16,702 --> 00:31:20,801
Um, my first boyfriend
rolled a homemade for me,

475
00:31:20,836 --> 00:31:22,667
which he could do
with one hand

476
00:31:22,702 --> 00:31:24,100
by the time he was 11.

477
00:31:24,135 --> 00:31:26,701
He dared me to inhale.

478
00:31:26,736 --> 00:31:28,767
I passed out cold,

479
00:31:28,802 --> 00:31:31,400
right into a patch
of poison sumac.

480
00:31:31,435 --> 00:31:34,701
Oh, boy.

481
00:31:34,736 --> 00:31:37,334
I came up with sores
that were so bad,

482
00:31:37,369 --> 00:31:42,334
I truly believed that I had
a visitation from the Lord.

483
00:31:45,167 --> 00:31:47,100
No, but I like it here.

484
00:31:47,135 --> 00:31:50,234
Well, I do wish that my roommate
would get a job in Alaska.

485
00:31:50,269 --> 00:31:53,200
And I wish that
the crazy guy

486
00:31:53,235 --> 00:31:55,767
would stop following me
to work every day.

487
00:31:55,802 --> 00:31:58,434
But we had a crazy guy
in Bethel, too.

488
00:31:58,469 --> 00:32:00,901
Delbert O'Dell.

489
00:32:00,936 --> 00:32:04,601
He would always hang out
in front of the Ben Franklin.

490
00:32:04,636 --> 00:32:07,167
But it was different,
because when I was younger,

491
00:32:07,202 --> 00:32:09,767
I could say, "Hey, Del,
it's time for you
to go home now,"

492
00:32:09,802 --> 00:32:13,033
and I knew that he wasn't
gonna rape me or--

493
00:32:13,068 --> 00:32:15,667
Del O'Dell?
Yeah.

494
00:32:15,702 --> 00:32:18,801
Older brother of Mel.

495
00:32:20,269 --> 00:32:23,000
But what about you?
I mean, what, uh--

496
00:32:23,035 --> 00:32:24,968
When did you have
your first cigarette?

497
00:32:25,003 --> 00:32:29,300
And do you have
a crazy guy in your town?

498
00:32:29,335 --> 00:32:32,534
Are those
your nicest shoes?

499
00:32:32,569 --> 00:32:36,801
Uh, are you, um...

500
00:32:36,836 --> 00:32:38,234
married?

501
00:32:43,334 --> 00:32:45,734
No.

502
00:32:47,434 --> 00:32:50,667
Okay. Um...

503
00:32:50,702 --> 00:32:55,133
So, uh,
on page 24...
24?

504
00:32:55,168 --> 00:32:58,434
Yeah, small typo.

505
00:33:00,035 --> 00:33:01,467
What did you give me?

506
00:33:01,502 --> 00:33:03,968
Sleepy Time?

507
00:33:04,003 --> 00:33:06,400
You give me Sleepy Time
at 10:00 in the morning?

508
00:33:06,435 --> 00:33:09,434
Listen--
You know who's coming in
today, Bernard Faber.

509
00:33:09,469 --> 00:33:12,033
Laurie--
The Amphibians Make
Good Pets guy.

510
00:33:12,068 --> 00:33:13,267
Laurie...
I'm gonna be asleep--

511
00:33:13,302 --> 00:33:15,934
Shut up!

512
00:33:17,133 --> 00:33:19,067
I think...

513
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:23,200
I think it's serious.

514
00:33:23,235 --> 00:33:26,501
What, you mean with the--

515
00:33:26,536 --> 00:33:28,467
Okay.

516
00:33:28,502 --> 00:33:30,334
No, it's getting serious.
Is that better?

517
00:33:30,369 --> 00:33:31,434
No, I didn't mean--

518
00:33:31,469 --> 00:33:33,567
Okay, okay.

519
00:33:33,602 --> 00:33:37,200
It's moving
in the direction
of serious.

520
00:33:39,367 --> 00:33:42,667
Ah...
Ah...

521
00:33:42,702 --> 00:33:44,734
It's serious.

522
00:33:47,033 --> 00:33:49,133
I think he's gonna
ask me, ya know?

523
00:33:49,168 --> 00:33:50,634
Oh, I know.

524
00:33:50,669 --> 00:33:51,968
You know?

525
00:33:52,003 --> 00:33:53,734
How would you know?

526
00:33:53,769 --> 00:33:55,901
Alright, now take
a deep breath, okay?

527
00:33:55,936 --> 00:33:58,267
It's an island.

528
00:33:58,302 --> 00:33:59,534
Again.

529
00:33:59,569 --> 00:34:01,067
Okay.

